title: For Sale:  US Civil War Confederate Kerr's Patent Revolver Rare London Armoury Co LAC .44 Kerr British
postcontent: PENNY START, TWO WEEK, NO RESERVE AUCTIONKerr's Patent Revolver, 3rd Variation; ca.1863 London Armoury Co.(LAC) Production/Confederate Issue; .44 Percussion; S/N: 9900Rare, Kerr's Patent Revolver...this percussion revolver was produced by the London Armoury Co at their England factory under contract with the government of the Confederate States of America. A highly-sought after piece on the collector's market, Kerr revolvers are among the few Confederate martial arms that may be identified by serial number. These revolvers were manufactured beginning in 1859, with Confederate agent Capt Caleb House signing a contract to purchase the LAC's entire output beginning in 1862. As such, Kerr's .44 Patent Revolvers falling between serial numbers 1019 and 10150 are considered to be within the range of weapons shipped by LAC via Fraser, Trenholm & Co. to the Confederacy. The revolver has all correct features, including matching serial numbers on the frame and cylinder, and the serial number places its production in late 1863 or early 1864. Although lacking the JS/Anchor mark, the grip does have the vacant panel, and it should be noted that many Kerrs with verified Confederate provenance are not so proofed. Called the 'Cavalry Model' by the Confederate army, the bulk of these revolvers are thought to have been distributed to Confederate cavalry units. Of note to the collector-the most famous record of these guns is the invetory of weapons logged by Julian Pratt of the 18th VA Cavalry Co. H. Known as Pratt's Roll, the document is incomplete, but lists 10 revolvers by serial number, all between 9240 and 9975. This places this revolver in close proximity to the guns on Pratt's list and may be considered to be within the Pratt range. An outstanding find for the collector, this Kerr's Patent revolver represents an extremely rare piece with strong investment potential.Condition:Fair overall, condition is closer to good with respect to Confederate-issued arms. The gun has desirably seen no refinish or restoration and wears its original LAC bluing, which is strongest on the lock plates. Bluing on the frame, barrel and cylinder are perhaps 20%, with the whole of the surface covered in moderate pitting, old dried grease, and black powder flash corrossion. Evident original bluing is present, with the patina trending toward russet and amber-there is no active rust on the gun. Markings are correct, with the serial number(often misidentified as the patent number) on the frame and cylinder matching. There are London House proof marks on the barrel and cylinder, with London Armoury Co. address on the lock plate and a second logo on the left of the frame. Additionally, the assembly number is present on the frame under the cylinder(pictured). Of note-the loading lever is a replacement and is in need of tightening. Grips rate as good with moderate wear to the checkering and no cracks or chips. As stated above, the grips are free of markings, proofing or cartouches. Original lanyard ring is present. Mechanically, the hammer holds cock and the trigger engages the hammer, while the trigger does not cycle the cylinder. The bore has evident rifling overlain with heavy consistent pitting running the length of the barrel on both grooves and lands.

title: For Sale:  Belgian 12 GA side by side
postcontent: **Update** Reduced price 10/10/17I have a 1923 Belgian 12 GA side-by-side shotgun. This gun has been in my family for a long time. This gun has all the standard provisional Liege Belgium proofs. There is a cursive “b” indicating the 1923 year, and all of the inspector marks are pre-1924. All 3 engraved serial number match indicating it is all original and it shows the gun was imported to New York state. I am inclined to believe that this was made by Georges Laloux because on the barrel flats there looks to be engraved "GL" which I have a photo of. I matched this mark when I googled Georges Laloux, and also found an image of a pamphlet showing this manufacturer made a 1923 hammerless model, but it appears they are very rare, as Laloux was big on the hammer model SXS shotguns. It is possible that I may have missed something but I have scoured the gun with a magnifying glass and this looks to be the manufactures mark. I am not a professional and in my area I found more on my own, as "experts" just label them guilds because they don't know the history or don't want to take the time to find out. I have many close up photos of proof marks, inspection marks, and trademarks available upon request. This is a hammerless, break away box locking system with assist open that functions flawlessly, it is an assist open, have a video of it functioning also available upon request. It has functioning slide "ejectors" for spent shells, but the shells are not ejected wholly - they slide away when broke open and make the spent shell easy to grab. Once the break-away is closed the firing pins automatically set for fire. It does have a manual slide safety switch. The gun fires well and can shoot modern light shells no problem. The barrels are NOT damascas. All of the mechanisms are flawless and operate perfectly the engravings are beautiful, but the gun is not without flaw. The barrels are in excellent shape boors are completely  smooth  and I had gunsmiths in the area look at it. There is a very very slight defect near end of left barrel, an imperfection not really noticeable to the naked eye except in a certain light/angle. I had the steel verified with gunsmiths due to this and there are no cracks, stress marks, or any splitting of any kind.  I had to point out, local gun appraisals did not notice this. I have shot modern light duty bird thru the gun, and gunsmith said should be fine, but a gun like this is more for collecting than firing but can be fired it shoots well actually.  If you are looking for a beautiful sxs this one is the right price. I have had this gun appraised and it has appraised twice at twelve hundred $ minimum. For these 2 appraisals the maker was not identified, now that I have done some leg work a   Georges Laloux hammerless from 1923 is rare. So I thought I would try listing it for a reduced price - as the gun is not without flaw, but in excellent shape. So I am listing at less than half of the appraised value due to the defect that I have pointed out up front. I can send pics of all of this to anyone upon request. If I cannot sell for $450 I will just keep the gun. I would like to sell it because I have other needs and a beautiful antique shotgun, while nice and somewhat sentimental…. doesn’t really do much for my other firearm needs, so I’m selling it to get what I need. Only trades considered would be AK and would have to be in very good condition, no junk. title: For Sale:  Ruger No.1 .45-70 Govt. 22 inch Lever Action Rifles
postcontent: The Ruger No.1 is a falling block , under-lever, single shot rifle which follows some of the Farquharson design characteristics but contains features never previously found in rifles of this type. The No.1 buttstock is mortised onto the receiver with a bolt passing through the stock into the receiver. The forearm is attached to a heavy steel extension from the receiver. The hammer is concealed and retracted by the first opening motion of the lever and can never strike the firing pin unless the breech block is fully elevated. The swinging transfer block virtually locks the firing pin forward against gas pressure during firing.It can be ship to local dealer if needed.

title: For Sale:  1923 Belgian 12 GA Side-by-side
postcontent:
I have a 1923 Belgian 12 GA side-by-side shotgun.  This gun has been in my family for a long time.  This gun has all the standard provisional Liege Belgium proofs.  There is a cursive “b” indicating the 1923 year, and all of the inspector marks are pre-1924.   All 3 engraved serial number match indicating it is all original and it shows the gun was imported to New York state.  I have many close up photos of proof marks and trademarks available upon request. This is a hammerless, break away box locking system with assist open that functions flawlessly.  It has functioning slide ejectors for spent shells.  Once the break-away is closed the firing pins automatically set for fire.  It does have a manual slide safety switch.  The gun fires well and can shoot modern light shells no problem.  The barrels are not damascas.  I have had this gun appraised and it has appraised twice at twelve hundred minimum.  Here is the interesting part, the maker trademarks are difficult to make out under the “crown”  I have researched this and I have someone else also helping me.  The thing is the estimated value and appraisals are “as is” without the maker determined as it sits in its condition and year.
 
Many people call these “guilds” because they don’t take the time to find the maker.  This gun could increase greatly in value, and in turn I would raise the price accordingly once the maker is determined.  I am continuing to research as I post this.  I would like to sell it because I have other needs and a beautiful antique shotgun, while nice and somewhat sentimental…. doesn’t really do much for my other firearm needs, so I’m selling it to get what I need.  No, I’m not interested in trades I know what I want to buy.  If I had the funds for my needs I would never sell it…  
 
The art work, engraving, checkered wood stock are all beautiful and in excellent condition.  Very nice side-by-side. $800 firm
Can email me or call or text.  Near Indianapolis.
Thanks, David  317-667-250five
